An excellent puzzler, who's aesthetic mimics the movies I grew up with really well. The controls are simple and intuitive, the graphics are oddly cute considering the subject manner, and the music is top notch.  I especially appreciate the design of the in-game store. It does an excellent job of recreating the look and feel of the old video rental stores I used to hit every week.  At a mere $2.99, Slayaway Camp is worth every penny, and more. And while I don't usually purchase cosmetic items, I'm probably going to drop the coin on the skin packs, just to support the developers.  Seriously, it's a seriously fun game. The puzzles are clever, and sometimes difficult, but never impossible.  Buy it.

Very fun, hats off to developers.

content: Yup, love it. Simple concept; not always simple solution.   The Family/PG rated gameplay really is fine for a young adult. Possible my tween helped with a solution or two!

The base gameplay itself isn't new for the most part, it is a sliding type puzzle that we've seen a few times.  They do add a number of their own different puzzle options as you go along though that make it pretty interesting.  The package they wrap it all up in is quite different and cool.  You are the killer, you're not a nice person at all.  Your motivations are to kill people (though it is shown as if they are movie scenes).  There are numerous killers that open as you play, and various interesting kills you can unlock.  Just remember at the base it is a sliding puzzler, not an action or adventure game.  This reminds me of a lot of original mobile titles you used to pay $1-$2 for and get a great amount of levels and fun content out of.  Baring in mind the price and high quality production values (and overall fun, etc) I've got to give this a top rating.
An awesome twist on strategy and horror. Easy to get into hard to master. Love it.
